\begin_layout Title
Computer Interfaced Science Experiments for B.Sc Physics Syllabus
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In science, theory and experiment are equally important.
 If experiments could be conducted on the topics that are covered in the
 theory classes, it would enhance the learning process.
 Most of the time this is not done due to lack of required equipment.
 Science experiments generally involve measuring/controlling physical parameters
 like temperature, pressure, velocity, acceleration, force, voltage, current
 etc.
 If the measured physical property is changing rapidly, the measurements
 need to be automated and a computer becomes a useful tool.
 For example, understanding the variation of AC mains voltage with time
 requires measuring it after every millisecond.
 Inter-University Accelerator Centre, a particle accelerator laboratory
 under UGC, has been involved in developing low cost equipment that can
 be interfaced to a computer to perform experiments.
 The expEYES kit is designed to support a wide range of experiments, from
 school to post graduate level.
 It also acts as a test equipment for experiments in electricity and electronics
 .
 Its simple and open architecture allows the users to develop new experiments,
 without getting into the details of electronics or computer programming.
 Details are available at http://expeyes.in
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are around fifty experiments documented in the user's manual of expEYES,
 but only a brief description of each activity is given.
 This document selects five experiments and present them in a form suitable
 to be included as a laboratory experiment at B.Sc level.
 Introducing a couple of them also gives the students an opportunity to
 get familiar with the equipment and perform many other experiments and
 demonstrations if they like.
\end_layout

