\begin_layout Standard
The theory of AC circuits is introduced in the 
\begin_inset Formula $12{}^{th}$
\end_inset

 standard and later at BSc level in more detail.
 How the amplitude and phase of an applied sinusoidal voltage vary across
 the circuit elements like resistors, capacitors and inductors are analyzed
 mathematically.
 Conducting this experiment and comparing the results with theory will enhance
 the understanding of the student considerably but it has not been done
 so far, mainly due to the difficulties in measuring amplitude and phase
 accurately.
 The expEYES kit can do this very easily.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:RC-Series-circuit"

\end_inset

(a) shows the RC circuit connections, crocodile clips are used for changing
 the components easily.
 The sinewave output is applied to a capacitor and resistor connected in
 series.
 The applied voltage is viewed on channel 1 (A1) and the voltage across
 the resistor is viewed on channel 2 (A2).
 The instantaneous values of the voltage across the capacotor is obtained
 by subtraction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Response-of-RC"

\end_inset

 shows the applied sine wave, voltage across the capacitor and the voltage
 across the resistor.
 The phase of the voltage across the resistor is same as that of the phase
 of the current though the circuit.
 It can be seen that the voltage across the capacitor is leading the current
 by 90 deg.
 The applied voltage and measured voltages across R and C are displayed.
 The voltage phase shift across the capacitor also is measured and displayed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As per the theory, the phase difference of the voltage across the capacitor
 in an RC circuit is given by the relation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi=\arctan\left(\frac{Z_{c}}{R}\right),where\, Z_{c}=\frac{1}{2\pi fC}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For f=150.7 Hz, C = 0.1
\begin_inset Formula $\mu F$
\end_inset

 and R = 1k
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

, Zc = 1056 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=46.6^{0}$
\end_inset

.
 The measured value is 
\begin_inset Formula $46.8^{0}$
\end_inset

.
 A calculator is provided inside the GUI program to evaluate this, it could
 also be done using the Python program listed below
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
from math import *
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
C = 1.e-6
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
R = 1000
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
f = 150.7
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
zc = 1./(2*pi*f*C)
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
phi = atan(zc/R)
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
print phi * 180 / pi  # convert to degrees
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the procedure will be repeated for different R and C values, it would
 be useful to modify the program to read the R and C values from the user.
\end_layout

